article.description: Diana Taurasi scored 32 points and the Phoenix Mercury clinched the top seed in the WNBA Western Conference playoffs with a 101-91 victory over the Sacramento Monarchs on Friday night.
article.headline: Phoenix cruises to win, locks up West's No. 1 seed
article.linkText: Mercury clinch No. 1 in West for first time since '97
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- The Phoenix Mercury chose water over
champagne for their locker-room celebration of a landmark regular
season.

	   If the Mercury can build on this success in the playoffs next
week, coach Paul Westhead probably can find something a bit more
bubbly for his players.

	   Diana Taurasi scored 32 points and the Mercury clinched the top
seed in the WNBA Western Conference postseason with a 101-91
victory over the Sacramento Monarchs on Friday night.

	   Cappie Pondexter had 23 points for the Mercury, who made a
season-high 15 3-pointers. They blew past the Monarchs in an
outstanding second half for their 10th victory in 11 games at the
close of the winningest regular season in franchise history.

	   "It's a nice feeling, but it's not like there's any
advantage," Westhead said of his club's top spot. "We're happy
we're playing well and winning. ... We just had a champagne
celebration -- with bottled water."

	   Phoenix's win also set the playoff picture in the West. The
Mercury, who are in the playoffs for the first time since 2000,
will face fourth-place Seattle in the best-of-three first round
next week, while the slumping Monarchs will meet second-place San
Antonio starting Thursday at Arco Arena.

	   Tangela Smith had 14 points and seven rebounds as Phoenix
finished first overall in the conference standings for the first
time since the WNBA's inaugural season in 1997. The Mercury
actually clinched the top spot right around the time they tipped
off at Arco Arena, when San Antonio finished up its 59-55 loss to
Indiana.

	   "It feels great," said forward Penny Taylor, who scored 12
points. "We've always been just on the edge of the playoffs."

	   Sacramento and Phoenix wrap up their regular seasons with
another meeting in Arizona on Sunday. The Mercury have won five
straight in the rivalry, and there's little reason to think any
opponent can slow them down if the defense-minded Monarchs can't do
it.

	   Rebekkah Brunson scored 17 points for the Monarchs, whose .500
play in August will keep them on the road when they begin defense
of their consecutive conference titles.

	   Sacramento couldn't keep up with the Mercury's fevered pace
despite using all 11 players in uniform, giving up a season-high in
points. Nicole Powell, Yolanda Griffith and Kara Lawson all scored
12 points apiece.

	   Monarchs coach Jenny Boucek was uncharacteristically blunt about
her club's halfhearted effort in its home finale.

	   "I know we can do much better," Boucek said. "We're much,
much better than that, and I hope we show it Sunday. It's all
pride. I don't care if we're out on the playground. That's not us,
and that's unacceptable for our team. We make things hard for
teams, and we didn't do that tonight."

	   Westhead's quick-strike offense sent the Mercury on a 20-6 run
in the second quarter, turning a small deficit into a 10-point
lead. Phoenix then scored 22 points in the opening 5:40 of the
third quarter, opening up a 19-point advantage moments later.

	   "The game was played at their pace, and there's very few teams
that can do that," Lawson said. "We're inconsistent. We had a
great first quarter, and then turnovers started. They led to easy
buckets, and we were way behind."

	   Taurasi scored 16 points in the second half, setting a season
high with 12 field goals. She also drew harsh boos from the
Sacramento crowd with a hard foul on Griffith in the final minutes.
